  <data key="d5">1770830635</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Statement Coverage">
  <data key="d0">Statement Coverage</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Statement coverage is a type of code coverage testing that involves writing test cases to execute each program statement.&lt;SEP&gt;Statement Coverage is a software testing technique that aims to execute every statement in a program at least once.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-1885c8cabab1027faeb9afbaf3f0ddc5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a9004c9fb37134adfd3b872db4e4a036</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830954</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Explicit Interfaces">
  <data key="d0">Explicit Interfaces</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Explicit Interfaces are documented interfaces.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d95d5a03291c8ae4834c72b31a85edc7</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830635</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Path Coverage">
  <data key="d0">Path Coverage</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Path coverage is a type of code coverage testing.&lt;SEP&gt;Path Coverage is a software testing technique that aims to cover all possible paths in a program.&lt;SEP&gt;Path Coverage is a software testing technique that involves splitting the program into a number of paths.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-1885c8cabab1027faeb9afbaf3f0ddc5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a9004c9fb37134adfd3b872db4e4a036&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-730afa5a03e337a9a1b2ed3ad640133d</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770831285</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Implicit Interfaces">
  <data key="d0">Implicit Interfaces</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Implicit Interfaces are known internally to the software engineers but are not documents.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d95d5a03291c8ae4834c72b31a85edc7</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830636</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Condition Coverage">
  <data key="d0">Condition Coverage</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Condition coverage is a type of code coverage testing.&lt;SEP&gt;Condition Coverage is a software testing technique that aims to test all possible outcomes of Boolean conditions in a program.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-1885c8cabab1027faeb9afbaf3f0ddc5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a9004c9fb37134adfd3b872db4e4a036</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830952</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Gray Box Testing">
  <data key="d0">Gray Box Testing</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Gray Box Testing is an approach where additional test cases are generated and included when architecture or design documents do not clearly explain all interfaces among components.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d95d5a03291c8ae4834c72b31a85edc7</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830637</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Bottom-Up Integration">
  <data key="d0">Bottom-Up Integration</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Bottom-up integration is the piecing together of systems to give rise to grander systems, thus making the original systems sub-systems of the emergent system.&lt;SEP&gt;Bottom-up integration is a software testing approach where integration starts from the bottom-level components up to the higher-level components.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d95d5a03291c8ae4834c72b31a85edc7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4a2a0fc342861ce4f51a3e5784bf82da</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830804</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Two-Way Decision Construct">
  <data key="d0">Two-Way Decision Construct</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">A two-way decision construct refers to if statements, where both the then and else parts need to be tested.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-1885c8cabab1027faeb9afbaf3f0ddc5</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830638</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Top-Down Integration">
  <data key="d0">Top-Down Integration</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Top-down integration is the breaking down of a system to gain insight into its compositional sub-systems.&lt;SEP&gt;Top-down integration is a software testing approach where integration starts from the top-level components down to the lower-level components.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d95d5a03291c8ae4834c72b31a85edc7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4a2a0fc342861ce4f51a3e5784bf82da</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830803</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Multi-Way Decision Construct">
  <data key="d0">Multi-Way Decision Construct</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">A multi-way decision construct refers to switch statements, where multiple test cases are needed to cover all possible switch cases.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-1885c8cabab1027faeb9afbaf3f0ddc5</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830639</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Bi-Directional / Sandwich Integration">
  <data key="d0">Bi-Directional / Sandwich Integration</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">A type of integration.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-d95d5a03291c8ae4834c72b31a85edc7</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830640</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Asynchronous Exceptions">
  <data key="d0">Asynchronous Exceptions</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Asynchronous exceptions, such as divide by zero errors, can prevent a test case from covering all statements in a code section.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-1885c8cabab1027faeb9afbaf3f0ddc5</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830641</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Boundary Conditions">
  <data key="d0">Boundary Conditions</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Boundary conditions in loops are situations where the loop is skipped, executed once, or executed a maximum number of times, often causing defects if not handled correctly.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-1885c8cabab1027faeb9afbaf3f0ddc5</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830642</data>
