  <data key="d2">Software quality refers to the degree to which software meets specified requirements and user needs.&lt;SEP&gt;Software quality relates to the degree to which a system meets requirements, customer needs, or expectations.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c7b18e88c7970da3d28ba996629ad181&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0c000d3c006e3afe689c5531f61cede1</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830958</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Process">
  <data key="d0">Process</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Process is the set of methods, practices, standards, documents, activities, policies, and procedures used to develop and maintain a software system.&lt;SEP&gt;Process refers to a source of defects caused by flawed or inadequate development processes.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c7b18e88c7970da3d28ba996629ad181&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-777f4f5fd36fe745076f0229587eef55</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770831241</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Software Specification">
  <data key="d0">Software Specification</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Software specification defines the functionality of the software and its operational constraints.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c7b18e88c7970da3d28ba996629ad181</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830773</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Software Development">
  <data key="d0">Software Development</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Software development involves producing the software to meet the specified requirements.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c7b18e88c7970da3d28ba996629ad181</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830773</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Integrity">
  <data key="d0">Integrity</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Integrity relates to a system's ability to withstand intentional and accidental attacks.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-7d1d7014ef279c74a7acb5889dca6440</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830773</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Portability">
  <data key="d0">Portability</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Portability relates to the ability of software to be transferred from one environment to another.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-7d1d7014ef279c74a7acb5889dca6440</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830773</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Software Validation">
  <data key="d0">Software Validation</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Software validation ensures the software performs as the customer expects.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c7b18e88c7970da3d28ba996629ad181</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830773</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Interoperability">
  <data key="d0">Interoperability</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Interoperability is the effort needed to link or couple one system to another.&lt;SEP&gt;Interoperability refers to the degree to which software can be connected easily with other systems and operated.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-7d1d7014ef279c74a7acb5889dca6440&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-50ee503f2fae49523a55b9fcdc5df8d1</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770831012</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Software Evolution">
  <data key="d0">Software Evolution</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Software evolution is the process of adapting the software to meet changing customer needs.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c7b18e88c7970da3d28ba996629ad181</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830775</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Software Quality Assurance Group">
  <data key="d0">Software Quality Assurance Group</data>
  <data key="d1">organization</data>
  <data key="d2">The Software Quality Assurance (SQA) group is a team ensuring necessary actions are taken during development so software conforms to technical requirements, working with project managers and testers.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-7d1d7014ef279c74a7acb5889dca6440</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830775</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Engineering">
  <data key="d0">Engineering</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Engineering is the application of scientific, economic, social, and practical knowledge to design, build, and maintain various systems.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-c7b18e88c7970da3d28ba996629ad181</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830776</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Project Managers">
  <data key="d0">Project Managers</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Project Managers work with the Software Quality Assurance Group and testers to develop quality-related policies and quality assurance plans.&lt;SEP&gt;Project Managers develop reasonable test plans.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-7d1d7014ef279c74a7acb5889dca6440&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-09aff991601cb8d11a8b32035d5ed5c8</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770831751</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Applicability Property">
  <data key="d0">Applicability Property</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">The Applicability Property states that for every program, there exists an adequate test set that properly tests it.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-346d26eb8b7a18c215c91e66c30d9495</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830800</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Nonexhaustive Applicability Property">
  <data key="d0">Nonexhaustive Applicability Property</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">The Nonexhaustive Applicability Property states that a tester does not need an exhaustive test set to adequately test a program.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-346d26eb8b7a18c215c91e66c30d9495</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830800</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Monotonicity Property">
  <data key="d0">Monotonicity Property</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">The Monotonicity Property states that if a test set T is adequate for program P, and T is a subset of T', then T' is adequate for program P.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-346d26eb8b7a18c215c91e66c30d9495</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830800</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Inadequate Empty Set">
  <data key="d0">Inadequate Empty Set</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">The Inadequate Empty Set property states that an empty test set is not an adequate test for any program.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-346d26eb8b7a18c215c91e66c30d9495</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830800</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Anti-Extensionality Property">
  <data key="d0">Anti-Extensionality Property</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">The Anti-Extensionality Property states that programs P and Q can be equivalent, and T is adequate for P, but T is not adequate for Q.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-346d26eb8b7a18c215c91e66c30d9495</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830801</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="General Multiple Change Property">
  <data key="d0">General Multiple Change Property</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">The General Multiple Change Property states that programs P and Q can have syntactic equivalence, and T is adequate for P, but not for Q.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-346d26eb8b7a18c215c91e66c30d9495</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830801</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Anti-Decomposition Property">
  <data key="d0">Anti-Decomposition Property</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">The Anti-Decomposition Property states that a program P and a component Q can be adequately tested, but the component Q may not be adequately tested.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-346d26eb8b7a18c215c91e66c30d9495</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830802</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Anti-Composition Property">
  <data key="d0">Anti-Composition Property</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">The Anti-Composition Property states that programs P and Q can be individually adequately tested, but the combined program P;Q may not be adequately tested by the same test set.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-346d26eb8b7a18c215c91e66c30d9495</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830802</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Program P">
  <data key="d0">Program P</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">Program P refers to a software program that is being tested.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-346d26eb8b7a18c215c91e66c30d9495</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830803</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Program Q">
  <data key="d0">Program Q</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">Program Q refers to a software program that is being compared to or composed with Program P.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-346d26eb8b7a18c215c91e66c30d9495</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830803</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Test Set T">
  <data key="d0">Test Set T</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Test Set T refers to a set of test data used to evaluate the adequacy of software testing.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-346d26eb8b7a18c215c91e66c30d9495</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830804</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Exhaustive Test Set">
  <data key="d0">Exhaustive Test Set</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">The Exhaustive Test Set includes testing on all representable points of a program, ensuring no other test data can be generated.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-346d26eb8b7a18c215c91e66c30d9495</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830805</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Depth First Approach">
  <data key="d0">Depth First Approach</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Depth first approach is a method for testing interfaces in a specific order.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-4a2a0fc342861ce4f51a3e5784bf82da</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830807</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Breadth First Approach">
  <data key="d0">Breadth First Approach</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Breadth first approach is a method for testing interfaces in a specific order.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-4a2a0fc342861ce4f51a3e5784bf82da</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830808</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="New Product">
  <data key="d0">New Product</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">A New Product refers to a new software being developed which requires integration and testing of its components.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-4a2a0fc342861ce4f51a3e5784bf82da</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1770830809</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
