<node id="Equivalence Class Partitioning">
  <data key="d0">Equivalence Class Partitioning</data>
  <data key="d1">method</data>
  <data key="d2">Equivalence class partitioning is a test case design technique that divides the input data into partitions, where all the values in one partition are expected to be treated the same by the system.&lt;SEP&gt;Equivalence Class Partitioning is a black box testing method used to divide the input domain into classes.&lt;SEP&gt;Equivalence class partitioning is a software testing technique for selecting test inputs by identifying a small set of representative input values that produce different output conditions.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-413abe27441aa74b0b434e98bea575fe&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4236e7b8427ccbaff16d4b0ef1506341&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5e67f594ae3047aebaed5c7bf8c5ee26</data>
